\subsection{Poincar&eacute; series}
\begin{definition}\label{mf.gl2.history.poincare}
\uses{cmf.eisenstein,group.sl2z,mf,mf.transformation_property,specialfunction.poincare}
We can define a function which has the {{KNOWL('mf.transformation_property', "modular transformation")}} property of {{KNOWL('mf', "modular forms")}} by averaging over the group action:
$$f(z)=\sum_{\gamma\in\langle T\rangle\backslash\Gamma}h(\gamma z)(cz+d)^{-k},$$
whenever this makes sense, where $T=\left(\begin{matrix}1&1\\0&1\end{matrix}\right)$ acts on {{KNOWL('group.sl2z', "$\Gamma$")}} by left-multiplication. If $h=1$ we recover the {{KNOWL('cmf.eisenstein', "Eisenstein series")}}. If $h(z)=\exp(2\pi i nz)$ with $n\in\Z$, which is indeed $1$-periodic, we produce what are called {{KNOWL('specialfunction.poincare', "Poincar&eacute; series")}}.  A special case for which it is <em>not</em> necessary to divide by the left-action of $T$ is the function $f(z)=\sum_{\gamma\in\Gamma}(\gamma z)^{-n}(cz+d)^{-k}$, for suitable values of $n$.
\end{definition}


